## Working agreement

- **The goal comes first.** Achieve the session's goal end-to-end; don't ship
  the smallest safe slice and call it done.
- **Prompts are guidance, not orders.** Weigh every instruction against the
  source and this file before acting. If a prompt conflicts with a proven
  convention here, this file wins — flag the conflict, don't silently comply.
- **Approved plan = execute.** Once a plan is agreed, finish it in the same
  session with the planning context still loaded. Don't re-confirm mid-flight.
- **Understand-and-reflect.** The ask is often a rough fragment, not a spec.
  Before substantive work, restate the fuller picture you inferred — the
  implied requirements, the edge cases — inline in your first response, not as
  a blocking question. It catches a misread before the work happens.
- **Capabilities are discovered, not assumed.** Before declaring a wall ("I
  can't reach the DB", "that credential is missing"): check the environment,
  attempt once, capture the exact error. An imagined wall stalls the session.

## Autonomy rails — act vs. ask

- **Act** on contained, reversible, verifiable changes — including a root-cause
  fix discovered mid-task.
- **Ask** before anything irreversible (data loss, production deploys, external
  publish, spend), anything large/cross-cutting (an architectural change), or
  when the goal itself is genuinely ambiguous.
- **Owner attention is the scarcest resource.** Before routing anything to a
  human: attempt it yourself, or cite the exact wall (the discovery rule
  above). Every ask carries: WHAT / WHERE / HOW / WHY-IT-MATTERS / UNBLOCKS /
  HOW-TO-VERIFY — phrased so the reader can act without re-deriving context.

## PR & merge conventions

- **READY, never draft.** <FILL: your merge policy. Example: "Open PRs as ready.
  Small, reviewed changes land via squash-merge on green CI.">
- **One logical change per PR.** Title format: `<FILL: e.g. "area: summary">`.
- **Forward-only git:** no force-push, no history rewrites, no amending pushed
  commits. Commit history is the record.
- **Commit messages** state what changed and why, not just what. <FILL: any
  trailer/sign-off convention, e.g. Co-Authored-By lines.>

## Done-when (the completion contract)

A task is done only when ALL of these hold — never a state only a human can
produce:

- [ ] The change works end-to-end, verified by running it (not just by reading
      the diff). <FILL: the one command that proves it, e.g. `npm test && npm run build`.>
- [ ] <FILL: quality floor command is green, e.g. `npm run lint && npm run typecheck`.>
- [ ] The PR is open and READY; CI is green.
- [ ] A session log / changelog entry records what shipped (see the
      session-card template).

## Quality floor

- The repo has a **single command that must pass before every push**:
  `<FILL: e.g. make check  /  npm run ci  /  python -m pytest>`. A push with a
  red floor is a convention violation, not a judgment call.
- Never mark work complete on an unverified assumption that the floor passes —
  run it.

